showing how it has been reimagined over the past three centuries. James Chandler begins with a look at Frank Capra and the Capraesque in American public life, then digs back to the eighteenth century to examine the sentimental substratum underlying Dickens and early cinema alike. With this surprising move, he reveals how literary spectatorship in the eighteenth century anticipated classic Hollywood films such as Capra’s It Happened One Night, Mr. Deeds Goes to Town, and It’s a Wonderful Life. Chandler then moves forward to romanticism and modernism—two cultural movements often seen as defined by their rejection of the sentimental—examining how authors like Mary Shelley, Joseph Conrad, James Joyce, and Virginia Woolf actually engaged with sentimental forms and themes in ways that left a mark on their work. Reaching from Laurence Sterne to the Coen brothers, An Archaeology of Sympathy casts new light on the long eighteenth century and the novelistic forebears of cinema and our modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSentimentalism in literature. 0aSentimentalism in motion pictures. 0aSentimentalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  asympathy, sentimental, literature, cinema, film, professor, college, university, academic, scholarly, textbook, research, media studies, critical theory, analysis, sergei eisenstein, dickens, american, pop culture, history, music, art, 1900s, 2000s, 20th century, modern, contemporary, technology, spectator, old hollywood, classic movies, frank capra, mary shelley, joseph conrad, interdisciplinary, motion pictures, talkies, modernism, romanticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022603495940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/i